q:
When would you want to use a remote repository rather than keeping all your work local?
a:
When I want to share my code with others or save my project as a buckup outside of my local machine

q:
Why might you want to always pull changes manually rather than having Git automatically stay up-to-date with your remote repository?
a:
remote changes may contain a lot of updates from diffent people working on the same project. If the programmer is not ready for the change programmer might get confused

q:
Describe the differences between forks, clones, and branches. When would you use one instead of another?
a:
branch is the way of diving a repository into multiple pathes. 
cloning is way of copying repository from one machine to another or from one directory to another inside a loccal machine 
forking is a way of copying repository from someone's github account to yours

q:
What is the benefit of having a copy of the last known state of the remote stored locally?
a:
The benefit is that you can compare and contrast to the remote branch while you are not online 
